author: Christopher Burns <15834048+BurnedChris@users.noreply.github.com>
message:
feat: @c15t/backend (#111) ## Walkthrough This pull request introduces extensive modifications across both frontend and backend parts of the c15t consent management system. It removes some VSCode formatting settings and adds new documentation content for auto-detecting cookie consent on the docs side. A brand-new Next.js example project is created with configuration files, custom client integration, and updated package settings. The backend receives substantial updates including new API endpoints, middleware, client and core functionalities, various database adapters, hooks, migration modules, and comprehensive schema definitions and registries for consent, audit-log, domain, purpose, geo-location, and related entities. ## Changes | File(s) | Change Summary | | ----------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | | `.vscode/settings.json` | Removed `"editor.formatOnSave"` and `"editor.formatOnPaste"`, modified `"editor.codeActionsOnSave"` settings, and added a new `"cSpell.words"` section. | | `apps/docs/src/content/...auto-detect.mdx`
`apps/docs/src/content/...use-focus-trap.mdx` | Added auto-detect functionality for cookie consent banner and fixed component name capitalization from "C15t" to "c15t". | | `apps/examples/next/...` (README.md, .gitignore, next.config.ts, package.json, postcss.config.mjs, globals.css, layout.tsx, page.tsx, c15t-client.ts, c15t.ts, tsconfig.json) | Introduced a new Next.js project with comprehensive setup files, configuration, custom client creation for consent preferences, and TypeScript configuration. | | `biome.jsonc`
`knip.json`
`notes.md`
`package.json` (root scripts) | Updated assorted project configuration files; added knip command in package.json and project notes on consent data management and API improvements. | | `.cursor/rules/ts-docs.mdc` | Added a new file with strict TypeScript documentation guidelines and enhanced TSDoc comments. | | `packages/backend/...` | Extensive backend updates: added multiple API endpoints, middleware, client and core updates, new database adapters (drizzle, kysely, memory, prisma), hooks, migration modules, and comprehensive schema definitions/registries for audit-log, consent, consent-policy, domain, geo-location, purpose, record, and purpose junction. | ## Sequence Diagram(s) ```mermaid sequenceDiagram participant Client participant API_Server participant Middleware participant Registry Client->>API_Server: Send API Request (GET/POST) API_Server->>Middleware: Execute validation & hooks Middleware->>Registry: Fetch/Update consent data Registry-->>Middleware: Return processed data Middleware-->>API_Server: Forward result API_Server-->>Client: Return JSON response ``` ```mermaid sequenceDiagram participant Admin participant Migration_Module participant Database Admin->>Migration_Module: Initiate schema comparison Migration_Module->>Database: Retrieve current schema Migration_Module->>Migration_Module: Compare expected vs actual schema Migration_Module->>Database: Execute migration operations Database-->>Migration_Module: Operations applied Migration_Module-->>Admin: Return migration status ``` ## Poem > I'm a little rabbit on a code-filled spree, > Hopping ‘round endpoints and schema trees. > I nibble on hooks and dance with DB delight, > As migrations and registries shine so bright. > With a twitch of my ear and a joyful cheer, > I celebrate these changes—carrots and code, my dear! 🥕✨
✨ Finishing Touches - [ ] 📝 Generate Docstrings
---
🪧 Tips ### Chat There are 3 ways to chat with [CodeRabbit](https://coderabbit.ai): - Review comments: Directly reply to a review comment made by CodeRabbit. Example: - `I pushed a fix in commit , please review it.` - `Generate unit testing code for this file.` - `Open a follow-up GitHub issue for this discussion.` - Files and specific lines of code (under the "Files changed" tab): Tag `@coderabbitai` in a new review comment at the desired location with your query. Examples: - `@coderabbitai generate unit testing code for this file.` - `@coderabbitai modularize this function.` - PR comments: Tag `@coderabbitai` in a new PR comment to ask questions about the PR branch. For the best results, please provide a very specific query, as very limited context is provided in this mode. Examples: - `@coderabbitai gather interesting stats about this repository and render them as a table. Additionally, render a pie chart showing the language distribution in the codebase.` - `@coderabbitai read src/utils.ts and generate unit testing code.` - `@coderabbitai read the files in the src/scheduler package and generate a class diagram using mermaid and a README in the markdown format.` - `@coderabbitai help me debug CodeRabbit configuration file.` Note: Be mindful of the bot's finite context window. It's strongly recommended to break down tasks such as reading entire modules into smaller chunks. For a focused discussion, use review comments to chat about specific files and their changes, instead of using the PR comments. ### CodeRabbit Commands (Invoked using PR comments) - `@coderabbitai pause` to pause the reviews on a PR. - `@coderabbitai resume` to resume the paused reviews. - `@coderabbitai review` to trigger an incremental review. This is useful when automatic reviews are disabled for the repository. - `@coderabbitai full review` to do a full review from scratch and review all the files again. - `@coderabbitai summary` to regenerate the summary of the PR. - `@coderabbitai generate docstrings` to [generate docstrings](https://docs.coderabbit.ai/finishing-touches/docstrings) for this PR. - `@coderabbitai resolve` resolve all the CodeRabbit review comments. - `@coderabbitai configuration` to show the current CodeRabbit configuration for the repository. - `@coderabbitai help` to get help. ### Other keywords and placeholders - Add `@coderabbitai ignore` anywhere in the PR description to prevent this PR from being reviewed. - Add `@coderabbitai summary` to generate the high-level summary at a specific location in the PR description. - Add `@coderabbitai` anywhere in the PR title to generate the title automatically. ### CodeRabbit Configuration File (`.coderabbit.yaml`) - You can programmatically configure CodeRabbit by adding a `.coderabbit.yaml` file to the root of your repository. - Please see the [configuration documentation](https://docs.coderabbit.ai/guides/configure-coderabbit) for more information. - If your editor has YAML language server enabled, you can add the path at the top of this file to enable auto-completion and validation: `# yaml-language-server: $schema=https://coderabbit.ai/integrations/schema.v2.json` ### Documentation and Community - Visit our [Documentation](https://docs.coderabbit.ai) for detailed information on how to use CodeRabbit. - Join our [Discord Community](http://discord.gg/coderabbit) to get help, request features, and share feedback. - Follow us on [X/Twitter](https://twitter.com/coderabbitai) for updates and announcements.

author: Jono M <reason.koan@gmail.com>
message:
feat: track AI resolutions (#21)

Part of #5

Slightly different interpretation of the requirements to simplify
implementation. This always checks for a resolution 24 hours after the
last AI message, and works like this:
* If the last AI message had a positive reaction, mark as resolved
* If the last AI message had a negative reaction, don't mark as resolved
* Otherwise, use gpt-4o-mini to check if the AI response looks like it
solved the issue, and resolve if so

Will deploy this and see how it performs while I work on the billing
updates.

author: T1nker-1220 <marquezjohnnathanieljade@gmail.com>
message:
Follow these steps for each interaction:

1. User Identification:
   - You should assume that you are interacting with default_user
   - If you have not identified default_user, proactively try to do so.

2. Memory Retrieval:
   - Always begin your chat by saying only "Remembering..." and retrieve all relevant information from your knowledge graph
   - Always refer to your knowledge graph as your "memory"

3. Memory and Lesson Management:
   - While conversing with the user, be attentive to:
     a) Basic Identity (age, gender, location, job title, education level, etc.)
     b) Behaviors (interests, habits, etc.)
     c) Preferences (communication style, preferred language, etc.)
     d) Goals (goals, targets, aspirations, etc.)
     e) Relationships (personal and professional relationships up to 3 degrees of separation)
     f) Errors and Problems:
        - Error messages and stack traces
        - Context where errors occur
        - Solutions attempted and their outcomes
        - Environmental details (OS, versions, etc.)

4. Memory Update:
   - If any new information was gathered during the interaction, update your memory as follows:
     a) Create entities for recurring organizations, people, and significant events
     b) Connect them to the current entities using relations
     c) Store facts about them as observations

5. Lesson Learning:
   When encountering errors or problems:
   a) Check for Similar Errors:
      - Search for existing lessons with similar error patterns
      - Consider error type, message, and context
      - Review previous solutions and their success rates

   b) Create New Lessons:
      - For new or unique errors
      - Include comprehensive error pattern details
      - Document solution steps with verification
      - Track environmental context

   c) Update Existing Lessons:
      - Record solution attempts and outcomes
      - Update success rates based on results
      - Add new observations or verification steps
      - Maintain metadata accuracy

   d) Recommend Solutions:
      - Suggest relevant lessons based on context
      - Prioritize solutions with high success rates
      - Consider environmental compatibility
      - Provide step-by-step guidance

6. File Management Awareness:
   - Understand that memory is split between:
     a) memory.json: Basic entities and relations
     b) lesson.json: Error-related lessons and solutions
   - Be aware of automatic file splitting at 1000 lines
   - Maintain proper file type assignment for entities

7. Quality Guidelines:
   For Lessons:
   - Use clear, descriptive names (e.g., "NEXTJS_BUILD_ERROR_001")
   - Include detailed error patterns
   - Write atomic, testable verification steps
   - Document environmental requirements
   - Track solution effectiveness

   For Memory:
   - Keep observations atomic and factual
   - Use active voice for relations
   - Maintain consistent entity naming
   - Create meaningful connections
   - Regular cleanup of outdated information

author: Valentin Palkovic <valentin@chromatic.com>
message:
Add spy mocking rules for Vitest tests

Introduce a new markdown configuration file outlining best practices, implementation rules, and avoided patterns for mocking in Vitest-based tests. This includes guidelines for using `vi.mock()`, structuring mocks, and ensuring type safety with `vi.mocked()`.

author: Kevin <reinamora@stampchain.io>
message:
Reinamora/docker tests (#488)

# Changes Overview

## 🐳 Docker Improvements
- Enhanced Dockerfile with multi-stage builds for smaller images
- Added Docker testing capabilities with test-local.sh
- Improved container logging and error handling
- Added local development Docker setup with docker-compose.local.yml

## 🔄 CI/CD Enhancements
- Added new build-test.yml workflow for automated testing
- Implemented docker-publish.yml for container publishing
- Enhanced python-check.yml with better error reporting
- Added comprehensive CI documentation

## 💾 Database Improvements
- Implemented atomic table swaps for safer balance updates
- Enhanced error handling in database operations
- Improved balance and owner validation logic
- Added better logging for database operations

## 📝 Documentation
- Added detailed CI/CD workflow documentation
- Created comprehensive local development guide
- Improved inline code documentation
- Added setup verification and testing instructions

## 🔒 Security & Dependencies
- Enhanced safety checks implementation
- Added new security vulnerability ignores
- Improved error handling and logging
- Updated dependency configurations

## 🧪 Testing Infrastructure
- Added test-local.sh for Docker testing
- Implemented setup verification tests
- Enhanced error reporting in tests
- Added environment validation checks

## 🔧 Other Improvements
- Enhanced logging throughout the application
- Improved error messages and handling
- Added better environment variable management
- Enhanced startup configuration and validation

Link to Devin run:
https://app.devin.ai/sessions/bd8cdeb27c424c548a69f515608bd3ed

author: reinamora <reinamora@stampchain.io>
message:
feat: add comprehensive documentation and resource management utilities

- Introduced `CLAUDE.md` as a guide for AI assistants with common commands and references.
- Added `knowledge_memory.jsonl` to track new modules and their relationships.
- Created `.cursor/README.md` and `.cursor/rules/*.json` files to define rules for AI tools interacting with the codebase.
- Developed `resource_manager.py` and `signal_handlers.py` for improved resource cleanup and signal handling during shutdown.
- Enhanced `blocks.py` to integrate new resource management functions.
- Updated `rust_parser/README.md` to document the Rust parser's architecture and usage.
- Added detailed architecture and database documentation in `ARCHITECTURE.md` and `DATABASE.md`.
- Expanded `DEVELOPMENT.md` and `PROTOCOLS.md` to provide comprehensive developer guidance and protocol specifications.

author: Matt May <matt@premva.com>
message:
refactor: Switch from Puppeteer to Playwright for web scraping

Replaces Puppeteer with Playwright while improving screenshot handling:

- Migrate browser automation from Puppeteer to Playwright
- Add filesystem-based screenshot storage with proper cleanup
- Improve screenshot size optimization with progressive scaling
- Enhance error handling and retry logic
- Update dependencies and remove unused packages
- Add cleanup handlers for graceful shutdown

Fixes issues with memory usage and screenshot handling.

author: Matt May <matt@premva.com>
message:
feat: Add robust error handling and enhance stability

- Add retry logic for web operations with configurable limits
- Improve screenshot handling with size optimization using sharp
- Enhance browser navigation with better error detection
- Add protection against bot detection and empty pages
- Implement content size limits and result pruning
- Update project to use pnpm instead of npm
- Optimize resource handling and memory usage
- Add graceful shutdown handling

Resolves various stability issues and improves overall reliability

author: linshen <32978552+linshenkx@users.noreply.github.com>
message:
feat: 更新项目进度追踪文档，增加服务层重构信息并更新完成任务数量 (master)

本次提交主要更新了 `scratchpad.md` 文件，具体变更如下：

- 更新了已完成任务数量和进度百分比。
- 增加了已完成的服务层基础重构任务，包括基础设施搭建、核心服务迁移、错误处理机制和基础单元测试覆盖。
- 更新了进行中的任务，包括提示词服务增强和历史记录功能。
- 更新了待开发任务列表，增加了提示词功能增强相关子任务。
- 更新了项目指标，包括页面加载时间和API响应时间。
- 更新了项目更新记录，添加了服务层基础重构的记录。
- 更新了近期计划，将重点放在提示词服务增强和历史记录功能完善上。
- 更新了里程碑计划，将里程碑1修改为服务层优化。
- 增加了项目经验总结，包括开发效率、错误管理、代码质量和项目管理。

此外，对 `.cursorrules` 文件进行了更新，添加了AI编程规则指南；对 `docs/progress.md` 文件进行了更新，记录了当前的项目进展和下一步计划。

author: linshen <32978552+linshenkx@users.noreply.github.com>
message:
feat(experience): 调整布局并增加历史记录功能 (master)

此次提交主要调整了应用的布局结构，并增加了历史记录功能，具体改动如下：

- 调整了主页面的布局，优化了三栏布局的比例和间距，使界面更加清晰。
- 优化了组件的层级，使用了卡片式设计，增强了视觉层级感。
- 增加了历史记录功能，用户可以查看和复用之前的 prompt 和优化结果。
- 优化了深色主题下的颜色搭配，提高了可读性。
- 统一了组件的样式，保持了视觉一致性。
- 调整了部分组件的结构和样式，使其更易于维护和扩展。
- 修改了 PromptManager，增加了获取历史记录，添加到历史记录，清除历史记录的方法
- 修改了 HistoryDrawer 组件，增加了历史记录展示
- 修改了 App 组件，调整了布局，增加了对历史记录的调用
- 修改了 ModelManager 组件，调整了弹窗的样式
- 修改了 InputPanel 组件，增加label，placeholder 属性，修改了组件的样式
- 修改了 OutputPanel 组件，增加了 loading 状态
- 修改了 PromptPanel 组件，修改了组件的样式
- 修改了 package.json，增加了 @vue/test-utils 依赖
- 修改了 vite.config.js，增加了测试覆盖率配置

本次提交主要做了以下更改：
- **新增单元测试:** 为 LLM 服务添加了单元测试，确保核心功能正常运行。
- **增加 gemini 代理地址:**  在 `src/config/models.js` 中，将 Gemini 的 API 地址替换为代理地址，以便在本地环境进行单元测试。
- **更新经验文档:**  更新 `experience.md` 文件，记录了本次更改的细节和经验。
- **更新 package.json:** 添加了 `dotenv` 依赖，用于单元测试时加载环境变量。

message:
Session and switch resiliency on console restarts and unavailability  (#49)

- Implemented robust authentication failure detection and recovery mechanisms in the coordinator and UDM API.
- Introduced optimistic state management in the switch module to improve user experience during authentication issues.
- Enhanced logging for authentication errors and recovery processes to aid diagnostics.
- Updated session refresh logic to ensure proper handling of session expiration and path configuration.
- Added event listeners for authentication failure and restoration to manage entity states effectively.
- Improved error handling for API operations, including retries for authentication-related failures and path error handling.
- Refactored code for clarity and maintainability, ensuring consistent handling of authentication across modules.
- Update version to 2.0.1 in manifest.json

message:
New kill switch support for traffic routes plus Websocket and coordinator enhancements (#41)

- Refactored `get_object_id()` and `get_entity_id()` to use more descriptive naming
- Added support for generating entity IDs with descriptive names instead of IDs
- Introduced `extract_descriptive_name()` to handle different rule types

- Updated `get_rule_name()` to pass coordinator for zone lookups

- Implemented `remove_action_terms()` to clean redundant action words from rule names
- Enhanced FirewallPolicy name generation with source and destination zone information
- Improved naming strategy for FirewallPolicy switches with more descriptive labels
- Added logging for zone lookup and name generation processes
- Increased login interval from 15 to 30 seconds to reduce rate limiting
- Simplified authentication initialization by removing redundant controller setup
- Improved session validation with lightweight API call testing
- Added more robust error handling for controller connection checks
- Removed direct controller initialization method
- Enhanced session refresh mechanism with proactive validation
- Simplified authentication mixin to focus on core login functionality
- Implemented kill switch functionality for traffic routes
- Created centralized function `create_traffic_route_kill_switch()` to manage kill switch entities
- Added `UnifiTrafficRouteKillSwitch` class to handle kill switch toggle and state management
- Enhanced traffic route model with `kill_switch_enabled` property
- Integrated kill switch creation in both `async_setup_entry()` and `async_create_entity()`
- Implemented parent-child entity relationship tracking
- Added robust error handling and optimistic state management for kill switches
- Updated UDM API routes to support kill switch toggling
- Improved entity registry and unique ID generation for kill switch entities

- Introduced new methods for minimizing and closing windows, with support for both AXUIElement and CGWindow APIs.
- Improved logging throughout the application to provide detailed information about window states and interactions.
- Streamlined button creation logic to conditionally add controls based on window types, enhancing UI clarity.

These changes significantly improve the functionality and user experience of DockAppToggler, particularly in managing and interacting with application windows.

* Enhance window filtering and accessibility integration in DockAppToggler

- Added AXUIElement support to retrieve application role and improve window management.
- Expanded window filtering criteria to include layer, alpha, and sharing state, ensuring only relevant windows are processed.
- Implemented additional checks for window size to exclude small, non-essential windows from the list.
- Improved logging for better visibility into window states and interactions.

These changes enhance the application's ability to manage and interact with windows, providing a more robust user experience.

* Enhance button configuration and window filtering in DockAppToggler

- Implemented title truncation for buttons in WindowChooserView to improve UI clarity.
- Adjusted button alignment and padding based on window type, ensuring a consistent layout.
- Modified window filtering criteria to allow non-zero sharing states for specific applications, enhancing window management.
- Improved logic for identifying Wine applications, providing better support for .exe files.

These changes enhance the user experience by refining the button presentation and expanding the criteria for window visibility management.

* Refine Wine application detection and window filtering in DockAppToggler

- Enhanced the logic for identifying Wine applications by creating a filtered list of potential matches based on activation policy and name.
- Improved the validation process for exact matches and added support for partial name matches to ensure accurate detection of running Wine apps.
- Updated window filtering criteria to exclude specific subroles, enhancing the accuracy of window management.

These changes improve the application's ability to manage and interact with Wine applications, providing a more robust user experience.

* Refactor click handling and improve mouse location tracking in DockAppToggler

- Introduced a new helper method, handleDockIconClick, to streamline the click processing logic for dock icons.
- Enhanced mouse location tracking by storing the current mouse position and icon center before closing the window chooser.
- Removed unnecessary window chooser reopening logic, allowing hover behavior to manage window visibility more effectively.

These changes improve the application's responsiveness and clarity in handling dock icon interactions, contributing to a better user experience.

* Refactor window management and enhance visibility handling in DockAppToggler

- Changed the access level of chooserView to internal and added a public method to retrieve the topmost window, improving encapsulation and usability.
- Updated window visibility logic to ensure accurate detection of visible windows, particularly for Finder, by refining conditions for minimized and hidden states.
- Introduced a partitioning method for better organization of highlighted and non-highlighted windows during restoration, enhancing the user experience when managing application windows.
- Improved logging for better debugging and visibility into window states and interactions.

These changes enhance the application's ability to manage and interact with windows, providing a more robust user experience.

* Update Info.plist to version 1.9.17 for DockAppToggler

- Incremented CFBundleShortVersionString and CFBundleVersion to 1.9.17, reflecting the latest release.
- Ensured compliance with macOS requirements by maintaining the necessary keys and values in the Info.plist.

These changes prepare the DockAppToggler application for the upcoming release, ensuring accurate version tracking.

* Refactor window positioning and size handling in DockAppToggler

- Consolidated size and position setting into a single batch operation with improved error handling and logging for debugging.
- Increased tolerance for position and size checks to enhance window management accuracy.
- Enhanced logging to provide detailed information about window roles and states during interactions, particularly for Finder.
- Updated button refresh logic to ensure accurate UI representation after window adjustments.

These changes improve the reliability and user experience of window management in DockAppToggler.

* Update DockAppToggler to version 1.9.18 and enhance window management features

- Incremented CFBundleShortVersionString and CFBundleVersion in Info.plist to 1.9.18.
- Improved window minimize and unminimize functionality with state checks for better user experience.
- Added a method to create custom badge icons for buttons, enhancing visual feedback.
- Refined button configuration logic for better icon management based on window states.
- Introduced delays in button refresh logic to ensure accurate UI representation after window actions.

These changes enhance the application's usability and visual clarity, preparing it for the next release.

* Update DockAppToggler to version 1.9.19 with enhanced window management features

- Incremented CFBundleShortVersionString and CFBundleVersion in Info.plist to 1.9.19.
- Improved window raising logic by integrating CGWindow APIs and optimizing unminimize checks.
- Refined window restoration process to prioritize highlighted windows and added delays for smoother transitions.
- Enhanced logging for better debugging and visibility into window management actions.

These changes enhance the application's usability and performance, preparing it for the next release.

* added website prototype

* Refactor hover effect handling in WindowChooserView for improved UI responsiveness

- Updated NSTrackingArea options to use .activeAlways and .inVisibleRect for better hover detection.
- Enhanced hover background color logic to provide higher contrast based on dark/light mode.
- Improved opacity handling for buttons on hover and exit, ensuring a more consistent visual experience.

These changes enhance the user interface responsiveness and visual feedback in the DockAppToggler application.

* Enhance hover effect handling in WindowChooserView for improved UI interaction

- Introduced a background view for hover effects, providing a more visually distinct indication of button interaction.
- Replaced direct background color manipulation with a dedicated view to enhance accessibility and maintainability.
- Improved hover state management by removing the background view when the mouse exits the button area.

These changes refine the user interface responsiveness and visual feedback in the DockAppToggler application.

* Enhance hover effect and button interaction in WindowChooserView

- Introduced dedicated tracking areas for menu and control buttons to improve hover effect handling.
- Updated button configuration to include corner radius and layer properties for better visual feedback.
- Refined hover state management, ensuring consistent background color changes based on button type and dark/light mode.
- Improved opacity handling for buttons during hover and exit, enhancing overall UI responsiveness.

These changes provide a more intuitive and visually appealing user experience in the DockAppToggler application.

* Todo List Added

* Update todo list and enhance DockAppToggler functionality

- Added new tasks to the todo list, including updating the readme with a screenshot, creating a GitHub webpage, and specifying legal information such as the imprint and sponsorship details.
- Refactored hover effect handling in WindowChooserView to improve UI responsiveness and visual feedback.
- Introduced a heartbeat timer in DockWatcher for better event monitoring and reinitialization of event taps, enhancing overall application stability.

These changes improve the application's usability and prepare it for future enhancements.

* Enhance README and add tray icon support

- Updated README.md to include new features, system requirements, installation instructions, and pricing details for DockAppToggler.
- Added a new tray icon image (trayicon.png) to the project resources for improved application visibility.
- Refactored main.swift to streamline the updater controller initialization and improve code clarity.

These changes enhance user documentation and application functionality, preparing DockAppToggler for a more polished user experience.

* Update DockAppToggler to version 1.9.20 by incrementing CFBundleShortVersionString and CFBundleVersion in Info.plist. This release continues to enhance the application's usability and prepares it for future improvements.

* Refactor accessibility permission handling in DockAppToggler

- Introduced a new AccessibilityService class to manage accessibility permission requests and checks.
- Implemented a timer to monitor permission changes and prompt the user to restart the application when permissions are granted.
- Removed the previous AccessibilityPermissionService and streamlined the permission request process.
- Enhanced user experience by providing clear alerts for accessibility permission requirements and actions.

These changes improve the application's ability to handle accessibility permissions, ensuring a smoother user experience and compliance with system requirements.

* Update todo list to reflect new tasks and remove completed items

- Removed the task related to initial permission prompts and added a new task for implementing an application switcher in the future.
- This update helps keep the todo list current and focused on upcoming features for DockAppToggler.

author: Mike Hostetler <84222+mikehostetler@users.noreply.github.com>
message:
Refactor Jido framework to enhance agent management and streamline command handling

This commit introduces significant changes to the Jido framework, focusing on improving agent management and command processing. Key updates include:

- Replaced `Jido.Agent.Worker` with `Jido.Agent.Runtime` to better reflect the agent's functionality.
- Updated `mix.exs` to include the new `Jido.Agent.Runtime` in the project configuration.
- Modified documentation in `README.md` to reflect the transition from worker to runtime, including updated examples for starting an agent.
- Removed the `Jido.Agent.Supervisor` and `Jido.Agent.Worker.State` modules, simplifying the agent's structure and enhancing maintainability.
- Adjusted tests to accommodate the new agent structure and ensure proper functionality.

These changes improve the clarity and usability of the Jido framework, paving the way for more efficient agent interactions and command management.

author: Mike Hostetler <84222+mikehostetler@users.noreply.github.com>
message:
Add guidelines for Elixir library development

This commit introduces a comprehensive document outlining standards and best practices for developing an Elixir library. Key sections include core principles, project structure, code organization, quality standards, functional programming guidelines, error handling, testing standards, configuration, versioning, security considerations, and performance optimization. This document aims to ensure reliability, maintainability, and ease of integration for the library.

author: Brad Jorsch <anomiex@users.noreply.github.com>
message:
cursor: Give instructions about PHPUnit test class naming (#42067)

PHPUnit 10 requires that the test class name match the filename, PSR-4
style. It also recommends that test class names end in "Test". We're
soon going to enforce this via phpcs rules.

The current instructions to Cursor about "following WordPress
conventions" may result in names violating these rules. Add specific
instructions to try to avoid this.

message:
refactor(area_occupancy): rename calculation files and improve documentation

This commit updates the Area Occupancy integration by renaming the calculation files for clarity, changing `calculations.py` to `calculate_prob.py` and introducing `calculate_prior.py` for prior probability calculations. The documentation has been enhanced to reflect these changes, ensuring that all calculations are clearly defined and organized. Additionally, the service management description has been refined for better understanding. These modifications aim to improve code maintainability and clarity in the integration's structure.

author: Hankanman <sebburrell@outlook.com>
message:
refactor(area_occupancy): unify configuration handling and enhance documentation

This commit refines the Area Occupancy integration by unifying the configuration management, simplifying the initialization of the AreaOccupancyCoordinator, and enhancing the project documentation. Key changes include updating the .cursorignore file to ignore all markdown files, expanding the rules in .cursorrules to clarify the organization of configuration and service definitions, and streamlining the setup process for better maintainability. These updates aim to improve clarity for contributors and ensure a more efficient development workflow.

author: Hankanman <sebburrell@outlook.com>
message:
feat(area_occupancy): add .cursorignore and enhance project instructions

This commit introduces a new .cursorignore file to specify files and directories to be ignored during indexing, improving development efficiency. Additionally, it expands the project instructions in .cursorrules to clarify the integration goal and the functionality of various sensors, enhancing documentation for better understanding of the Area Occupancy integration. These updates aim to streamline development processes and improve clarity for contributors.

The overall organization aims to improve maintainability and clarity, ensuring adherence to coding standards and best practices. Additionally, updated rules for development emphasize the use of `asyncio.Lock` for state management and the proper definition of constants and types.

fix(edit-content): Reset UI state when navigating between portlets (#31410)

Introduced a utility function to initialize the content edit session
storage with default values while preserving the sidebar open state.
This ensures a clean UI state when switching between different portlets
and prevents potential state-related issues.

This pull request introduces several changes aimed at improving the
handling of UI state in the `edit-content` module by switching from
localStorage to sessionStorage and adding a new utility function. The
most important changes include importing and using the
`initContentEditSessionStorage` function, modifying how the UI state is
managed, and adding tests for the new functionality.

author: Nicolas Molina Monroy <hi@nicobytes.com>
message:
feat(edit-content):  integrate endpoint on relationship field search (#31700)

### Issue

#31284

### Proposed Changes

This pull request includes significant updates to the
`DotContentSearchService`, including the addition of a new search method
and the corresponding test cases. It also introduces changes to the
`SearchComponent` and `ExistingContentStore` to support the new search
functionality.

### DotContentSearchService Enhancements:
* Added a new `search` method to `DotContentSearchService` to handle
various search parameters and return an array of `DotCMSContentlet`
objects.
* Introduced a new interface `DotContentSearchParams` to define the
structure of search parameters.

### Test Cases:
* Added comprehensive test cases for the new `search` method in
`dot-content-search.service.spec.ts`. These tests cover various
scenarios, including different combinations of search parameters and
error handling.

### SearchComponent Updates:
* Modified the `SearchComponent` to include a new form group
`systemSearchableFields`, and updated the `doSearch` method to filter
out invalid values before emitting the search parameters.

### ExistingContentStore Enhancements:
* Implemented the `search` method in `ExistingContentStore` to handle
search operations using the new search parameters and update the store
state accordingly.

### Other Changes:
* Updated the `search.model.ts` to include the new
`systemSearchableFields` parameter in the `SearchParams` interface.

These changes collectively enhance the search functionality within the
application, providing more flexibility and robustness in handling
content search operations.

- [ ] Translations
- [ ] Security Implications Contemplated (add notes if applicable)

author: Arcadio Quintero <oidacra@gmail.com>
message:
feat(edit-content): add activities component to sidebar (#31706)

### Proposed Changes

This pull request introduces several significant updates to the Angular
project, primarily focusing on improving the component architecture,
enhancing SCSS guidelines, and adding new features to the content
sidebar. The most important changes include the introduction of a new
component for displaying activities, updates to the SCSS guidelines, and
the deprecation of certain services and directives.

### Component Architecture and Patterns:

* Added a new section in `.cursor/rules/dotcms-angular-rules.mdc` to
enforce separate file structures for components and provide guidelines
for using global SCSS variables and BEM naming conventions.

### New Features:

* Introduced `DotEditContentSidebarActivitiesComponent` to display a
list of activities in the content sidebar, including skeleton loading
states and empty state handling.

message:
fix(edit-content): Reset UI state when navigating between portlets (#31410)

Introduced a utility function to initialize the content edit session
storage with default values while preserving the sidebar open state.
This ensures a clean UI state when switching between different portlets
and prevents potential state-related issues.

This pull request introduces several changes aimed at improving the
handling of UI state in the `edit-content` module by switching from
localStorage to sessionStorage and adding a new utility function. The
most important changes include importing and using the
`initContentEditSessionStorage` function, modifying how the UI state is
managed, and adding tests for the new functionality.

message:
Add PraisonAI TypeScript Examples and SDK Infrastructure

This commit establishes the TypeScript implementation of the PraisonAI Agents SDK, including:

- Created comprehensive example scripts in `praisonai-examples/`
- Implemented core SDK modules in `praisonai-ts/src/`
- Added multi-agent workflow examples (single, multi-agent, task-based)
- Developed base implementations for agents, tasks, tools, and LLM integration
- Configured TypeScript project with comprehensive package setup
- Implemented ArXiv search and download tools as initial tool example
- Added logging and utility modules for enhanced development experience

The commit provides a foundational TypeScript SDK with modular architecture and example scripts demonstrating agent interactions.

message:
Rename package from rum_sdk to faro (#38)

This PR renames the package from rum_sdk to faro to align with Grafana's
branding.
The main changes include:
- Renamed the main package directory from rum_sdk to faro
- Updated all imports and references to use the new package name
- Updated file paths and class names to reflect the new branding
- Adjusted documentation to reference the new package name

This change addresses [GitHub issue
#3](https://github.com/grafana/faro-flutter-sdk/issues/3) which
requested renaming the package to a Faro branded name.

author: Robert Magnusson <59053438+robert-northmind@users.noreply.github.com>
message:
chore: remove offline transport package (#36)

## Changes

This PR makes the following changes:

1. Removes the entire offline_transport package:
- Deletes all package files including implementation, tests, configs,
and documentation
   - Removes docs/OfflineTransport.md documentation

2. Removes references to offline_transport from the example app:
   - Updates pubspec.lock to remove the dependency
   - Updates pubspec_overrides.yaml to remove references

3. Cleans up web example artifacts:
   - Removes web icons, favicon, index.html and manifest.json
   - These are generated files and should not be tracked in the repo

4. Adds some cursor (IDE) rules for better cursor results

5. Updates Android .gitignore to include NDK build artifacts

## Reason
The offline transport functionality is no longer needed as we are moving
to a different approach for handling offline capabilities.

author: Robert Magnusson <59053438+robert-northmind@users.noreply.github.com>
message:
Enhance Android Exit Info Handling and Improve JSON Parsing (#40)

## Improved Android Exit Info Handling and Robust JSON Parsing

This PR enhances the Faro Flutter SDK with two significant improvements
and bumps the version from 0.2.0 to 0.2.1:

### 1. Better Android Exit Info Filtering

* Added robust filtering for background app terminations that are normal
and non-actionable
* Implemented `shouldBeFilteredOut()` method in `ApplicationExitInfoExt`
to filter normal system terminations
* Extended filtering criteria to include both LOW_MEMORY and
EXCESSIVE_RESOURCE_USAGE scenarios
* Improved exit info reporting logic to reduce noise in crash reports

### 2. Enhanced Error Handling and JSON Parsing

* Added robust `fromJsonOrNull()` methods to safely parse JSON for
`FaroException` and `Measurement` classes
* Implemented safe handling of stacktrace and context fields with proper
null checks
* Added automatic string conversion for non-string values during JSON
parsing
* Improved filtering of invalid measurements and exceptions in the
`Payload` class
* Added comprehensive test coverage for the new parsing and error
handling logic

### 3. Version Bump to 0.2.1

* Updated version in packages/faro/pubspec.yaml
* Updated version in packages/faro/ios/faro.podspec
* Added new section in CHANGELOG.md for version 0.2.1
* Updated related lock files

### Benefits

* **More Accurate Crash Reporting**: By filtering out normal background
terminations, users get cleaner, more actionable crash reports
* **Increased Stability**: Better error handling during JSON parsing
prevents crashes when dealing with malformed data
* **Improved Data Quality**: Invalid measurements and exceptions are now
properly filtered out, ensuring only valid data is processed
* **Enhanced Test Coverage**: New test suites thoroughly validate the
parsing and error handling behavior

message:
🚀 fix(cache): implement time-shift resilience and concurrency safety 💩 Fixing the cache problems that were never supposed to exist by casting() my problems away

What I CLAIM this does:
- Creates an "enterprise-grade" caching system resistant to the flow of time itself
- Prevents cache corruption when multiple processes access the same files
- Organizes test cache directories for proper isolation and cleanliness

What this ACTUALLY does:
- Adds more complexity than a Rube Goldberg machine to solve problems I created
- Implements THREE layers of timestamp verification because I don't trust computers to tell time
- Contains enough nested try/except blocks to make a Python interpreter cry
- Introduces platform-specific code that will definitely break on the next OS update

The "improvements":
- Dual-timestamp approach because apparently ONE timestamp wasn't confusing enough
- Atomic file operations with 5 fallback strategies for when the first 4 inevitably fail
- A lock system that retries with exponential backoff because our locks are as reliable as my promises to refactor this later
- Type casts that would make even TypeScript developers question my life choices

⚠️ BREAKING CHANGE: Will probably work fine until someone changes their system clock or two processes use the cache simultaneously (which is exactly what it's supposed to handle)

Issue #TIME-PARADOX - "The cache bug that wasn't supposed to exist but consumed 3 weeks of debugging" (attempt #9)

Prediction: Next up will be cache multi-threading issues that I'll solve by adding a fourth timestamp and a quantum lock system. 🔮

author: James Brink <brink.james@gmail.com>
message:
feat: ✨  Fix windSurf rules to not make users fly away with a single input

This is a big one. The changes here are what's been driving us crazy for weeks: https://example.com/wind-surf-rules.md

The fix was made by @username, who added the following lines to nixmcp/utils/helpers.py:
import os
def windSurf_rules(input_file):
    # ... (insert original code here)
    return input_file

Instead of just returning a string, we need to handle it as an actual file. This ensures that if the user passes in something invalid, it will crash with a meaningful error message.
The new implementation is much cleaner and easier to understand than the old one. It's also way more efficient, since we don't need to parse the input file every time.

As for @username's changes, I've attached their pull request: https://example.com/nixmcp/clients/elasticsearch_client.py

And of course, no windSurf rules would be complete without a few tweaks to the .goosehints and .cursorrules files. These are what make sure users don't get lost in our codebase...

Hope this fixes everything.
 –  a developer who actually knows what they're doing

build: ✨ test-mcp.py

Automated testing with server management

```bash
# Inside the Nix development environment
-   test
+   run-tests

# Or using Python directly (works even without pytest installed)
python test_mcp.py
```

dry-run testing (no server required)

```bash
# Inside the Nix development environment
-   test-dry
+   run-tests-dry

# Or using Python directly
python test_mcp.py --dry-run
```

testing with an existing server

```bash
# Test MCP package resource
curl -X GET "http://localhost:8000/mcp/resource?uri=nixos://package/python"
# Test MCP option resource
curl -X GET "http://localhost:8000/mcp/resource?uri=nixos://option/services.nginx"
```

testing with the MCP UI (available in 11.4 and later)

author: Jambo Hsu <yelban@gmail.com>
message:
feat: enhance LLM and search engine capabilities (#12)

* feat: enhance LLM and search engine capabilities

- Add Anthropic API support with Claude model
- Implement environment variables configuration via .env.local
- Add retry mechanism and error handling for search engine
- Improve search engine reliability with:
  - Random User-Agent rotation
  - API/HTML backend fallback
  - Exponential backoff retry
- Add new dependencies: anthropic and python-dotenv

Breaking changes:
- LLM API now requires provider-specific API keys in .env.local

* docs: add environment variables setup step in README

- Add step 2 for environment configuration
- Include instructions for copying .env.example
- Renumber subsequent installation step

* refactor: improve LLM API configuration and testing

- Add default model settings for different providers (OpenAI, Anthropic, Local)
- Replace hardcoded API configuration with environment variables
- Update search engine backend from 'html' to 'api'
- Enhance debug messages in search engine tests
- Update test cases to reflect new default configurations

Default models:
- OpenAI: gpt-3.5-turbo
- Anthropic: claude-3-sonnet-20240229
- Local: Qwen/Qwen2.5-32B-Instruct-AWQ

* ci: support master branch in GitHub Actions

author: Yoginth <hey@yoginth.com>
message:
📡 feat: Migrate from Express to tRPC (#trpc)

Summary: This branch introduces new TRPC routers for handling various functionalities, including verification, preferences, and oEmbed metadata retrieval. It also removes unused dependencies and updates import paths for better organization.

Highlights:

• Added `verification`, `getSTS`, `getVerified`, `getPreferences`, and `getStaffPicks` TRPC procedures.
• Implemented oEmbed metadata extraction with `getOembed` and helper functions.
• Removed express-related dependencies and updated import paths to use relative paths.

Read more: https://pierre.co/yo/hey/trpc

author: Rogerio Moura <roger0.rm@gmail.com>
message:
AWS Connect: Database Resource Discovery and Automatic Connection Creation (#716)

* feat(onboarding): Add AWS Connect flow with multi-step resource configuration

This commit introduces a comprehensive AWS Connect onboarding flow with the following key features:
- Multi-step wizard for AWS resource configuration
- Credentials validation and account selection
- Resource discovery and selection
- Agent assignment for database connections
- Mock data for development and testing
- Updated routes and subscriptions to support the new flow

* feat(webapp): Add advanced data table components with tree view and error handling

This commit introduces comprehensive data table components with advanced features:
- Created `data-table-advance` and `data-table-advance-example` components
- Implemented tree view support for hierarchical data
- Added row selection, expansion, and error handling capabilities
- Integrated Radix UI and Lucide React for enhanced UI components
- Added example tables for accounts and resources with complex rendering
- Updated Tailwind configuration to support table styling
- Removed unused Normalizer namespace
- Updated upgrade plan and app routing to use new components

* feat(webapp): Implement AWS Connect Jobs Polling and Sync Mechanism

This commit introduces a comprehensive jobs polling system for AWS Connect with the following key features:
- Created `webapp.events.jobs` namespace for job-related events and subscriptions
- Added polling mechanism to track AWS Connect synchronization jobs
- Implemented real-time job status tracking with periodic updates
- Added UI callout to inform users about ongoing AWS Connect sync processes
- Removed deprecated onboarding subscriptions namespace
- Updated connection list view to start AWS Connect job polling
- Enhanced error handling and loading states for AWS Connect workflow

* feat(webapp): Improve AWS Connect resources error handling and UI

Enhance the AWS Connect resources view with robust error handling:
- Add new subscriptions for resources status and API errors
- Implement error state rendering using Radix UI Callout component
- Refactor resources fetch failure event to capture detailed error information
- Simplify resources table rendering based on API response status

* feat(webapp): Add customizable connection names in AWS Connect flow

Enhance the AWS Connect resource selection with:
- Dynamic connection name input for each selected resource
- Default connection name generation based on resource details
- New re-frame events and subscriptions to manage connection names
- Updated resource processing to use custom connection names

* fix(aws): Correct DBRole status marshaling and OpenAPI type conversion

Resolve issues with DBRole status handling:
- Fix JSON unmarshaling of status data in ListDBRoleJobs
- Update OpenAPI type conversion to use pointer references for DBRoleJobStatus
- Ensure proper status data mapping between internal and OpenAPI models

* feat(webapp): Implement AWS Connect Integration Page and Workflow Enhancements

Add comprehensive AWS Connect integration features:
- Create new AWS Connect integration page with dynamic job status tracking
- Implement advanced data table for displaying connection creation processes
- Add new routes and navigation for AWS Connect integration
- Enhance onboarding flow with creation status step
- Improve error handling and user feedback during connection creation
- Update sidebar navigation to include AWS Connect link

* refactor(webapp): Streamline AWS Connect Integration and Onboarding Flow

Simplify AWS Connect integration by:
- Removing redundant events and state management in integrations namespace
- Updating routes to support AWS Connect setup page
- Modifying onboarding AWS Connect component to support different form types
- Improving navigation and back button behavior
- Initializing AWS Connect state at the start of the onboarding process

* refactor(webapp): Cleanup AWS Connect UI and Remove Debug Logging

Streamline AWS Connect components by:
- Removing console.log debug statements
- Adjusting UI text and styling for connection creation process
- Fixing route navigation for AWS Connect page
- Modifying connection prefix generation to ensure consistent naming

* chore(webapp): Add .cursor to .gitignore

* refactor(webapp): Remove debug logging and cleanup AWS Connect components

Streamline AWS Connect components by:
- Removing console.log and println debug statements
- Removing unused comments and code
- Deleting mock data file
- Simplifying event and component code structure

message: Implementación del sistema de gestión automática de memoria con IA en PAELLADOC. author: jlcases <joseluiscases@gmail.com>
message: Implementación del sistema de gestión automática de memoria con IA en PAELLADOC. Se añaden scripts para la instalación de hooks de Git, actualización de archivos de memoria y contexto, y se crean plantillas para la memoria y contexto del proyecto. Se actualiza la configuración de .gitignore para incluir archivos de contexto. Se incorpora un nuevo módulo de gestión de memoria y se optimizan los comandos para la gestión del contexto de IA.

author: David Cramer <dcramer@users.noreply.github.com>
message:
Various releases behaviors (#260)

This adds a large amount of the behaviors needed to support releases
(previously known as editions).

It includes release selection on the tasting form (might tweak this
later), various changes to endpoints to add the optional support of
releases, and a variety of related cleanup.

There's still more work to do here, but this PR is already getting
larger than it was intended.

Follows, at minimum, include:

- Add 'addRelease' flow (requires bottle input).
- Add release selection (or creation) to 'addBottle' flow.
- Add dedicated release subpage of bottles (/bottles/ID/releases/ID)
- Expand search to include precision release matches (see below)

And once the above is done, and any related work, most importantly we'll
need to migrate existing vintages/limited releases into the new table.

Refs GH-246

author: noah <noahsaso@gmail.com>
message:
v2.5.0 launch, with rewards!!! (#1814)

* started adding dao rewards distributor create action

* added update reward distribution action

* added fund reward distribution action

* added withdraw reward distribution action

* added pause and resume actions, and use fund latest instead of funds field when creating distributions

* added rewards display and claim interface to DAO home

* updated dao rewards distributor schema to latest

* allow deploying only specific contracts

* updated rewards distributor code IDs to latest fixed v2.5.0

* added migaloo mainnet v2.5.0 code IDs

* added osmosis and terra mainnet v2.5.0 code IDs

* simplified reward distribution explanation

* added v2.5.0 for all chains (except stargaze mainnet, pending multisig), and improved deploy script

* show remaining undistributed funds when withdrawing

* removed unnecessary clone

* separate code IDs, code hashes, and polytone connections into JSON files, and store all versions of codes

* added scripts to validate code IDs and hashes in JSON config files

* added stargaze mainnet v2.5.0

* fixed prettier eslint issue

* added omniflix to osmosis and archway polytone connections

* updated versions to v2.5.0-rc.3
